[Pertussis has been on the increase throughout most of the world. This has been attributed in part to increased virulence and other genetic changes in the circulating clones of _Bordetella pertussis_, as well as waning or an ineffective immune response after vaccination. For a discussion of these problems, see moderator LL's comments in prior ProMED-mail posts on pertussis.

The incidence rate of pertussis among infants exceeds that of all other age groups, and the majority of deaths continue to occur among infants younger than 3 months of age. Because much of the morbidity and mortality from pertussis are in infants less than one year of age, especially less than 6 months, who are not as yet protected by active immunization, the CDC recommends "cocooning," a vaccination strategy that aims to protect infants from becoming infected with pertussis before the baby's whooping cough vaccinations start at 2 months of age, by vaccinating individuals, such as the mother and other caregivers, who would come into regular contact with the newborn infant.

In response to her pertussis vaccination, a pregnant woman will produce protective antibodies, which are passed transplacentally to her baby before birth. These antibodies provide the baby short-term protection against whooping cough in early life. Protective antibodies are at their highest about 2 weeks after getting the vaccine. So vaccination should be scheduled late in pregnancy, preferably during the 27th through 36th week, to give the baby the most protection when born and vaccination should be repeated with each pregnancy so high levels of protective antibodies are transferred to each of the babies.

Pregnant women should receive Tdap [combined tetanus, diphtheria, and pertussis vaccines, with a reduced dose of the diphtheria and pertussis vaccines], the type of pertussis vaccine for those 11 years and older, including pregnant women. Women who did not receive the vaccine during pregnancy should get it immediately after giving birth. Fathers, grandparents, and others 11 years and older who have close contact with the baby should also get a dose if they have not had the booster.

DTaP is the type of pertussis vaccine used for children 2 months through 6 years of age. Children should get 5 doses of DTaP, one dose at each of the following ages: 2, 4, 6, and 15 through 18 months and 4 through 6 years. Both the Tdap and DTaP vaccines combine protection against pertussis, tetanus and diphtheria (see http://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/adults/rec-vac/pregnant/whooping-cough/get-vaccinated.html). - Mod.ML]
